<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Books_mentioned_in_the_lectures">Books mentioned in the lectures</span></h2>
<ul>
<li>Jesse Schell: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0123694965/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0123694965&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">The Art of Game Design: A Book of Lenses</a> - What shall I say? One of the best books ever! Funny, self-deprecating, but so knowledgeable and fantastically written. This and the Deck of Lenses is a must for every game and gamification designer.<br />
(And then also: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0615218288/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0615218288&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">The Art of Game Design: A Deck of Lenses</a> - These is a deck of 100 cards with all the lenses that Jesse mentions in his book. A good way to use in practical exercises.)</li>
<li>Katie Salen, Eric Zimmerman <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0262240459/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_il_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0262240459&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">Rules of Play: Game Design Fundamentals</a></li>
<li>Raph Koster <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1932111972/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_il_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=1932111972&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">A Theory of Fun for Game Design</a></li>
</ul>
<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Additional_Interesting_Books_on_Gamification">Additional Interesting Books on Gamification</span></h2>
<ul>
<li>Mario Herger: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://amzn.com/1470000644">Enterprise Gamification - Engaging people by letting them have fun. Vol 01.</a> EGC Media, 2014, <a href="/wiki/index.php/Special:BookSources/9781470000646" class="internal mw-magiclink-isbn">ISBN 978-14-70000-64-6</a>.</li>
<li>Mario Herger: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://amzn.com/1500567140">Gamification in Human Resources. Vol 03.</a> EGC Media, 2014, <a href="/wiki/index.php/Special:BookSources/9781500567149" class="internal mw-magiclink-isbn">ISBN 978-15-00567-14-9</a>.</li>
<li>Mario Herger: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://amzn.com/1500720844">Gamification in Banking &amp; Financials. Vol 04.</a> EGC Media, 2014, <a href="/wiki/index.php/Special:BookSources/9781500720841" class="internal mw-magiclink-isbn">ISBN 978-15-00720-84-1</a>.</li>
<li>Mario Herger: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://amzn.com/1501071440">Gamification in Community &amp; Innovation Management. Vol 05.</a> EGC Media, 2014, <a href="/wiki/index.php/Special:BookSources/9781501071447" class="internal mw-magiclink-isbn">ISBN 978-15-01071-44-7</a>.</li>
<li>Mario Herger: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://amzn.com/1502856026">Gamification in Sales &amp; Support. Vol 06.</a> EGC Media, 2014, <a href="/wiki/index.php/Special:BookSources/9781502856029" class="internal mw-magiclink-isbn">ISBN 978-15-02856-02-9</a>.</li>
<li>Mario Herger: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://amzn.com/1502856093">Gamification in Healthcare &amp; Fitness. Vol 07.</a> EGC Media, 2015, <a href="/wiki/index.php/Special:BookSources/9781502856098" class="internal mw-magiclink-isbn">ISBN 978-15-02856-09-8</a>.</li>
<li>Janaki Kumar, Mario Herger: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://amzn.com/8792964079">Gamification At Work: Designing Engaging Business Software.</a> Interaction-Design.org, 2013, ISBN </li>
<li>David Williamson Shaffer: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.barnesandnoble.com/listing/2683590554801?r=1&amp;cm_">How Computer Games Help Children Learn</a> - forward by James Gee.</li>
<li>Gabe Zichermann: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1449397670/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=1449397670&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">Gamification by Design: Implementing Game Mechanics in Web and Mobile Apps</a> - A perfect practitioner guide for getting started with gamification.</li>
<li>Karl M. Kapp: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1118096347/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=1118096347&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">The Gamification of Learning and Instruction: Game-based Methods and Strategies for Training and Education</a> - If you are in the training and education space, you cannot not have this book. It shows how education and training in both schools/universities and corporations will change, and why. You can download a free <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.astd.org/Publications/Blogs/Learning-Technologies-Blog/2012/04/The-Gamfication-of-Learning-Sample-Chapter">sample chapter</a> from <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.astd.org/">astd.org</a>.</li>
<li>Jon Radoff: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0470936266/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0470936266&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">Game On: Energize Your Business with Social Media Games</a> - Jon Radoff rocks! A deep analysis of what makes games funs and how they tick, with tons of learnings for gamification.</li>
<li>Lee Sheldon: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1435458443/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=1435458443&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">The Multiplayer Classroom: Designing Coursework as a Game</a> - Especially useful for teachers, lots of practical advice and real-life examples of classes designed as games.</li>
<li>John Ferrara: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1933820144/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=1933820144&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">Playful Design</a> - An approach to gamification and the playfulness from a UX-designer's perspective.</li>
<li>Byron Reeves: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/142214657X/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=142214657X&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">Total Engagement: Using Games and Virtual Worlds to Change the Way People Work and Businesses Compete</a> - Byron Reeves spoke about games in enterprises, when the term gamification was not yet coined. Here he and his co-author talk about why games work in corporations, and show some great examples.</li>
<li>Jane McGonigal: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0143120611/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0143120611&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">Reality Is Broken: Why Games Make Us Better and How They Can Change the World</a> - If you are new to gamification and want to get inspired, this is the book to start with. After reading it, you want to know more about the power of games in real world context.</li>
<li>Dan Pink: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1594484805/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=1594484805&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">Drive: The Surprising Truth About What Motivates Us</a> - Dan Pink brings a number of examples that contradict conventional wisdom. For example that monetary rewards actually decrease engagement of people with work.</li>
<li>Ernest Adams, Joris Dormans: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0321820274/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_il_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0321820274&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">Game Mechanics - Advanced Game Design</a> - A deep dive into game mechanics. Really great!</li>
<li>Michael Hugos: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1449319564/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=1449319564&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">Enterprise Games - Using Game Mechanics to Build a Better Business</a> - Michael Hugos wrote the first comprehensible, and fact-based book on gamification in the corporate world</li>
<li>Bernard Suits: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/155111772X/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=155111772X&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">The Grasshopper: Games, Life and Utopia</a></li>
<li>James P. Carse <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B004W3FM4A/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=B004W3FM4A&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">Finite and Infinite Games</a> - James P. Carse makes the case to regard life as a game. This way every failure becomes a learning experience, every step one of progressing through the game. This results in taking life more playful and without sliding into depression. </li>
<li>Charles Duhigg: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1400069289/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=1400069289&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">The Power of Habit: Why We Do What We Do in Life and Business</a> - An interesting introduction in how habits are formed and how they can be changed. Perfect for gamification designers, who want to change the habits of their users. </li>
<li>Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0061339202/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_il_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0061339202&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">Flow: The Psychology of Optimal Experience</a> - This book shines a bright light on the idea of flow, revealing the criteria for entry into a state of flow. Flow could be viewed as a feeling of complete immersion in an activity, where one loses touch with everything outside of the current activity.</li>
<li>Stephen Anderson: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0321725522/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_il_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0321725522&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">Seductive Interaction Design</a> - A very nice book on user experience design that contains a really good section on gamification. </li>
<li>Herbert L. Petri: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1111841098/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=390957&amp;creativeASIN=1111841098&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">Motivation: Theory, Research and Application</a> - 6th Edition of this book expands nicely on behaviorism and cognitive motivation with the last chapter discussing emotions as motivators.</li>
</ul>
<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Gamification_References_From_Literature.2FFiction">Gamification References From Literature/Fiction</span></h2>
<ul>
<li>Orson Scott Card: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0812550706/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_il_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0812550706&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">Ender's Game</a> - Ender's Game is a classic sci-fi novel that was published in the early 80s and presents gamification</li>
<li>Ernest Cline: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0307887448/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_il_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0307887448&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">Ready Player One</a> - a gamified reality has taken over a dystopian society and its super-wealthy founder leaves in his last will &amp; testament the ultimate prize for the winner of the ultimate quest in this virtual world</li>
<li><p>Charles Stross: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://openlibrary.org/works/OL2465684W/Halting_State">Halting State</a> - A fun science-fiction of taking gamification to the extreme, cyberpunk style. In particular the real-world implication of maintaining the economic balance of a MMORPG and the real-world interface are very interesting. And the book is a treat for any Scottish nationalist&#160;;-)</p></li>
<li><p>Daniel Suarez: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/Daemon-Daniel-Suarez/dp/0451228731/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1349181798&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=daemon">Daemon</a> - A designer of computer games dies, leaving behind a program that unravels the Internet's interconnected world. It corrupts, kills, and runs independent of human control. It's up to Detective Peter Sebeck to wrest the world from the malevolent virtual enemy before its ultimate purpose is realized: to destroy civilization.</p></li>
</ul>
<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="Gamification_References_from_Film">Gamification References from Film</span></h2>
<ul>
<li><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.google.co.uk/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=2&amp;cad=rja&amp;ved=0CDQQFjAB&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FThe_Last_Starfighter&amp;ei=3btZUKDQJ7CN0wWl5IHQAw&amp;usg=AFQjCNGnwf2S78G9pvw4QZksLHN8xtRf2Q">The Last Starfighter</a>, where an alien race is installing a video game to identify assess candidates for starfleet pilots on Earth, specifically considering that Earth at that point had not connected with other civilizations in outer space. The film is from 1984, but already illustrates concepts like tailoring your system to a target group and use a gamified system for the area of recruiting, an application so far not widely used in the real world. </li>
</ul>
<h2> <span class="mw-headline" id="A_bit_off_topic.2C_but_still_relevant">A bit off topic, but still relevant</span></h2>
<ul>
<li>Benjamin Gilad: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://openlibrary.org/books/OL16865274M/Business_war_games">Business War Games - How large, small and new companies can vastly improve their strategies and outmaneuver the competition</a> - While this book maybe fits better in the serious games category, it is relevant for the gamification context in two aspects, 1) it transfers the war game concept into the business context and 2) it analyses the game elements and design principles that make for a successful war game in great detail.</li>
<li>Nicola Whitton, Alex Moseley: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0415897726/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_il_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0415897726&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=enterprisegam-20">Using Games to Enhance Learning and Teaching: a beginners guide</a> - a good critical starting point for the wider field of games-based-learning (education focus), which covers gamification along with deeper integration of game principles.</li>
</ul>

